Dropsync fills up all your phone memory with files to a point where it's useless. If you delete files to free up memory, it deletes them from dropbox too. It took me a while to realize that dropsync did more damage than benefit.  You can always access your dropbox files from the phone you do not need dropsync.
replyContent: App syncs files into your device. If you configured a big folder in Dropbox to be synced, then it would do exact that. There is a safety check, sync stops with error before completely filling device storage. If you choose two-way sync, deletion in device means deletion in Dropbox. This is powerful tool and can be dangerous if it's misconfigured.

Does exactly what I was looking for for ages - simple two way folder sync. I don't understand why Dropbox don't do it themselves. Best 4,99 I spent on an app.

Initially I thought I wouldn't need an automated two-way sync app for Dropbox since I can manage all my up- and downloads manually. Boy was I wrong when I started modifying my homescreen for hours a day. Uploading fonts, icons, and wallpapers, deleting them, taking screenshots etc. A constant back and forth of data that became extremely tedious to manage. Then I finally gave in and bought the PRO key for dropsync so I could set up different folders to sync automatically.  The setup process takes some time and you should make sure you have the folders already created to make it smoother. The initial sync will take some time depending on the amount of data (and connection speed of course). The background sync then is hardly noticeable and surprisingly fast. The only issues I've had were due to flaky WiFi connection and not dropsync's fault. A great tool for people that need to have data ready on multiple devices.

I'd like to sync my photo folder with Dropbox for the pictures taken with my phone but then also sync fully my Dropbox account.  The problem now is that I either need to setup about 20 individual sync folders to do this or end up with my photos being duplicated.  (E.g. uploaded to Dropbox because of one setting and downloaded again into my full Dropbox download folder.)  I wish I could setup one sync for photos and one that would automatically sync all remaining folders to a general Dropbox folder.  Also wish the pro version included a widget to trigger dropbox sync,

Save a game, and it is automatically synced to my dropbox and computer.   Easy to use and runs with low resources in the background. Highly suggest buying the full version.

I'm happy this app adds functionality that dropbox has neglected to address and it is a benefit to be able to access my files through my android tablet.  However, there are major problems that need to be fixed.  After four days I still haven't achieved a full sync.  To be fair my dropbox contains over 21 gb and 57000 files but for business users I would think it is not so abnormal.  It also highlights a problem with the way the app goes about syncing.  It appears that instead of only making changes to files that have been changed the app rescans every file every time it starts a sync.  Thus, when it doesn't finish the whole sync (for instance when having to go to work interrupts the progress the app has made overnight) or when going home interrupts the progress made while I'm at work) it appears to start over with the scanning on the new attempt. I've also noticed the sync go idle even though it has a connection, battery charge is within set parameters and the sync is not complete. Edit:  After over a week I still haven't gotten a full sync. Looks like it is the idling that's the main issue as it restarts the sync after every idle.  I'll be looking for another service.

Incredibly good developer support. This excellent app does everything it says, and does it well. Be aware that file datestamp issues are a failing of dropbox, not this app. Also note that remotely deleting pics/music may leave orphaned index entries for the now missing file in the gallery/music app. This is a bug in android, not this app! Use SDrescan app to fix if necessary. Unchecking 'instant upload' will minimize this, if a nuisance, by giving a chance to locally delete bad pics, just taken, before they get onto other devices, only to be deleted by the app leaving a dead index entry there. This is a first-class app and a must for any dropbox user.
